WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:04.910
Yeah, so I'm Aurool and Jakard is

00:00:04.920 --> 00:00:10.160
the @proto library that I wrote.

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:14.390
And yeah, first, I'm going to do a bit

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:15.820
about me.

00:00:15.830 --> 00:00:19.320
I'm an embedded and at this point everything else developer.

00:00:19.330 --> 00:00:21.200
I design electronics.

00:00:21.210 --> 00:00:24.220
Atproto kind of hit me like a truck like it

00:00:24.260 --> 00:00:26.320
did a lot of people here.

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:29.980
And yeah, got kind of -- yeah, very, very

00:00:29.990 --> 00:00:31.000
into it.

00:00:31.010 --> 00:00:33.990
I was trying to figure out something that felt right to contribute

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.600
to the atmosphere, a bunch of different things.

00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:40.560
And yeah, this is -- Jakard and a few different

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:43.790
things I've done are -- yeah, what you might call

00:00:43.790 --> 00:00:45.820
spite-driven development.

00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:48.990
This was a point where -- yeah, we had -- there

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:52.580
were plenty of atproto libraries at the time, but

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:55.530
they all kind of sucked to work with, especially back when

00:00:55.530 --> 00:00:56.240
I started.

00:00:56.270 --> 00:00:58.910
There were a couple of notable exceptions, but none of them

00:00:58.910 --> 00:01:01.370
were in Rust, which was my language of choice for a

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:03.340
bunch of reasons to get into.

00:01:03.350 --> 00:01:07.090
I ended up putting another project on hold because I got frustrated

00:01:07.090 --> 00:01:11.020
and some other friends had similar conversations.

00:01:11.030 --> 00:01:19.170
And yeah, a lot of this came down to issues

00:01:19.170 --> 00:01:26.760
with code generation from -- yeah, from lexicons,

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:30.210
GraphQL, everything you generate, you have how you specify

00:01:30.210 --> 00:01:35.940
what you want, and then you need code that does that

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:39.650
, you either hand write it or more likely you generate it

00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:42.680
from some state, be that JSON, be that GraphQL

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:44.240
, be that whatever.

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:48.840
And unfortunately, most of these fucking suck.

00:01:48.850 --> 00:01:51.360
You end up -- so you generate all the -- you generate

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:52.410
all your bindings.

00:01:52.490 --> 00:01:54.850
You spend way more time, or these days, LL

00:01:54.900 --> 00:02:02.760
M tokens writing code around them to make them actually usable.

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:06.200
This isn't just an app problem, but it hurts more

00:02:06.200 --> 00:02:09.660
here, both because lexicons and a lot of them

00:02:09.660 --> 00:02:12.870
, and especially in the ecosystem for people wanting to not just

00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:15.260
play in Blue Sky Sandbox.

00:02:15.270 --> 00:02:17.320
But we do not have to live like this.

00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:20.590
And in as much as this talk is about the thing that

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:23.210
I'm doing, it's also a, no, this

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:26.890
is something everybody else can do in whatever language, whatever you

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:33.780
can -- we can do this better, especially now.

00:02:33.790 --> 00:02:40.230
And so, yeah, it's like why Rust for me

00:02:40.230 --> 00:02:40.860
?

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:43.870
This was my language, and it is kind of at this

00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:48.680
point the only language you can run it literally pretty much anywhere

00:02:48.710 --> 00:02:51.820
, and it's actually not completely stupid.

00:02:51.830 --> 00:02:54.150
You can run a lot of things a lot of places,

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:57.180
but you would be hard to find defensible reasons.

00:02:57.190 --> 00:02:59.560
You can at least find defensible reasons for Rust, although

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:02.830
there's -- if you're running Rust on your full stack

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:06.300
, you better be my kind of pervert.

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:11.490
Yeah.

00:03:11.510 --> 00:03:20.330
And so, yeah, it has a -- excuse me --

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:23.180
it has a reputation as a difficult and demanding language.

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:27.500
The reputation is sort of deserved and sort of not.

00:03:27.510 --> 00:03:30.240
And, of course, a lot of Rust libraries go a

00:03:30.250 --> 00:03:32.710
long way to improving on that state.

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:35.650
And, of course, yeah, it's like one of

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:40.120
the reasons why I am a fan of it is that,

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:45.200
essentially, like, especially coming, for me, from the

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:47.600
sea world, the things Rust forces you to think of,

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:50.490
the things that people consider demanding difficult, are the things you

00:03:50.510 --> 00:03:54.500
need to think of anyway, and it makes them explicit.

00:03:54.510 --> 00:03:56.850
And, of course, like, the whole point, we

00:03:56.910 --> 00:04:00.320
can make the sharp edges easier if we care to.

00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:01.320
Yeah.

00:04:01.330 --> 00:04:07.110
And, again, we do not have to live like this

00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:07.680
.

00:04:07.690 --> 00:04:09.440
And, of course -- and this is the thing -- this

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:15.090
is peripheral to sort of the whole talk, but this is

00:04:15.110 --> 00:04:18.330
one of the things that I came out -- ran into that

00:04:18.330 --> 00:04:22.610
I didn't necessarily expect in the development of Jaccard

00:04:22.610 --> 00:04:22.820
.

00:04:22.830 --> 00:04:25.760
And it's basically parse don't validate can only take you

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:26.320
so far.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:28.640
This is kind of a truism that you get,

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:32.900
and especially among Rust devs, among functional programmers.

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:35.400
But the thing is that, like, there's a limit

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:39.320
, especially depending on how your language handles errors.

00:04:39.330 --> 00:04:40.320
Yeah.

00:04:40.330 --> 00:04:42.230
If surdayjson or surdaycbor can't

00:04:42.230 --> 00:04:45.500
parse something as the type you're asking of it, you

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:46.690
will just get an error.

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:49.380
It does not give you the partial.

00:04:49.390 --> 00:04:53.220
And this is not something that I've got a good solution

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:53.820
for.

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:56.840
But it also -- but that lack of good solution for it

00:04:56.890 --> 00:04:58.900
gets us to a different place.

00:04:58.910 --> 00:05:00.970
And -- hang on.

00:05:01.010 --> 00:05:11.090
I've just got -- and so, yeah

00:05:11.090 --> 00:05:12.940
.

00:05:12.950 --> 00:05:14.990
And so, yeah, it's like atrium previous go

00:05:14.990 --> 00:05:16.300
-to at ProtoRustCrate.

00:05:16.300 --> 00:05:20.110
They had typed numbers, the number -- it wasn't just

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:23.340
int 60 -- i64, i32, i8.

00:05:23.350 --> 00:05:25.850
It had a -- it would have a type, and that

00:05:25.850 --> 00:05:28.700
type encoded the limits, which is cool.

00:05:28.730 --> 00:05:30.400
It's very -- it's very interesting.

00:05:30.410 --> 00:05:31.830
In theory, in practice, it's a huge pain in

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:34.320
the ass, and this is partially the fault of Rust.

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:38.500
Rust type system does not handle that very well.

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:41.840
And Jaccard, until recently, mostly just put these

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:44.390
as code comments and generated APIs.

00:05:44.410 --> 00:05:46.550
Just fix that.

00:05:46.610 --> 00:05:49.300
And yeah, it's kind of the thing.

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:52.310
And yeah.

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:55.090
And of course, one of the challenges is, like,

00:05:55.090 --> 00:05:58.020
you've got methods for partial understanding.

00:05:58.030 --> 00:06:01.840
And this is something that I've really tried to push as

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:06.600
far as possible in this without -- where you can have arbitrary

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:07.230
